Style

Appearance of pages

  • You can control the appearance of pages (templates) with style files
    • HTML tags
    • CSS files
      • Colors, fonts, spaces, borders

HTML tags: Headings and paragaphs

<h1>Instructions</h1>

  <h2> Part 1 </h2>

      <p>In the first part of the experiment you are going to choose between couples of lotteries. </p>

[...]
  • Headings (titles subtitles)
    • Highlight the headings with tags `<h#> </h#>
      • Hyerarchical structure
        • <h1> Section</h1>
          • <h2> Subsection </h2>
            • <h3> Subsubsection </h3>
  • Paragraphs
    • Block of text on a new line <p> YOR TEXT HERE </p>

HTML tags: tables


[...]
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">#</th>
            <th scope="col" colspan="2" style="text-align:center">A</th>
            <th scope="col" ></th>
            <th scope="col" colspan="2"  style="text-align:center">B</th>
            <th scope="col"></th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">1</th>
            <td > p/10 of A<sub>1</sub>  </td>
            <td> (1-p)/10 of A<sub>2</sub></td>
            <td style="font-weight: bold">{{ form.HL }}</td>
            <td>p/10 of B<sub>1</sub></td>
            <td >(1-p)/10 of B<sub>2</sub> </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
        </table>
  • Table allows to arrange text in rows and columns
    • Typical structure
      • ```html
        Header 1 Header 2 Header 3
        1 2 3
        4 5 6
  • Rows <tr> </tr>
  • Column names <th> </th>
  • Cells <td> </td>

Style up your pages

  • To provide your pages with a coherent and adequate style you can use a css file
  • In you app create a folder named static and a subfolder with the name of your app (similar to what you do for images)
    • Put your file .css in that path
      • Colors, fonts,
  • To call your .css file insert this in your templates
{% block styles %}
<style type="text/css">
</style>
<link href="{% static "styles/mystyle.css" %}" rel="stylesheet">
{% endblock %}

  • To change the appearance we apply the following style changes in our mystyle.css

.box {

Icons

  • You can add icons to your pages
    • A repository of icons can be found at Iconify
      • Lets say you wan to add these icons to your template
  • Where you want to insert the icons in the .html template
<span class="iconify" data-icon="logos:css-3" data-inline="false" ></span>
<span class="iconify" data-icon="logos:html-5" data-inline="false"></span>
<span class="iconify" data-icon="logos:javascript" data-inline="false"></span>
  • In the .html template then add
{% block scripts %}
<script src="https://code.iconify.design/1/1.0.7/iconify.min.js"></script>
{% endblock %}

Multilanguage

Apps in different languages

  • In many circumstances, you may want to have your app in different languages
    • Experimens in differen tcountries
    • Development with foreign colleagues
  • Wrong solution
    • Write an app in each language
      • As an example, Italian, English,
    • If you make changes you must change all your apps
      • Apps might not be fully consistent
  • Right solution
    • Write your app in one reference language and then translate the templates
      • All changes are centralized

Template

{% extends "global/Page.html" %}
{% load otree i18n %} <!-- load this -->
{% load otree static %}

{% block title %}
    {% trans 'Page Title' %}
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}

{% trans 'Here we translate' %}

    {% next_button %}

{% endblock %}
  • Add {% load otree i18n %} in the opening of your page
  • The text to be translated must be within the tag {% trans TEXT TO BE TRANSLATED %}
    • Here, we transalte from English to Italian

Commands

    1. In your app main folder create a subfolder named locale
    1. In the app main folder run the command

    django-admin makemessages -l it

    • The letters after -l identify the destination language (here Italian)
    1. In subfolder locale there is a file django.po that can be edited with the translation

File django.po


# SOME DESCRIPTIVE TITLE.
# Copyright (C) YEAR THE PACKAGE'S COPYRIGHT HOLDER
# This file is distributed under the same license as the PACKAGE package.
# FIRST AUTHOR <EMAIL@ADDRESS>, YEAR.
#
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Project-Id-Version: PACKAGE VERSION\n"
"Report-Msgid-Bugs-To: \n"
"POT-Creation-Date: 2020-11-26 21:32+0100\n"
"PO-Revision-Date: YEAR-MO-DA HO:MI+ZONE\n"
"Last-Translator: FULL NAME <EMAIL@ADDRESS>\n"
"Language-Team: LANGUAGE <LL@li.org>\n"
"Language: \n"
"MIME-Version: 1.0\n"
"Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8\n"
"Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit\n"
"Plural-Forms: nplurals=2; plural=(n != 1);\n"

#: templates/language/MyPage.html:6
msgid "Page Title"
msgstr ""

#: templates/language/MyPage.html:11
msgid "Here we translate"
msgstr ""
  • At each msgstr " " we insert the Italian translation
    • As an example,
      • for msgid "Page Title" we write msgstr "Titolo"
      • for msgid "Here we translate" we write msgstr "Qui traduciamo"
  • After we translate everything, we give the command from the app main folder

django-admin compilemessages

  • This creates the file django.mo
    • This command must be run every time you add a translation
  • To run the italian version change the language code in settings.py
    • LANGUAGE_CODE = 'it' (en for English)

Dynamic graphs

Responsive graphs

  • It is possible to draw dynamic responsive graphs (see PGG)
    • We rely on Highcharts library under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0

Code

  • In subfolder static/name_of_app we insert
    • The JavaScript file hihcharts.js
      • Library needed to create the graph
    • The JavaScript file miografico.js
      • Contains a function to draw the graph
  • In the template the graph is inserted with
    • id=graph should match $('#graph').highcharts({ ...
     <div class="col-sm-6">
         <div id="graph" style="width:100%; height:300px;"> </div>
     </div>
function draw_graph(history_contrib,round_number){
  $('#graph').highcharts({
      chart: {
          type: 'line'
      },
      title: {
          text: 'Total earnings from the project'
      },
      xAxis: {
        allowDecimals: false,
         accessibility: {
            rangeDescription: 'Range: 1 to 10'
        }
      },
      yAxis: {
          title: {
              text: 'Points'
          }
      },
        plotOptions: {
        series: {
            label: {
                connectorAllowed: false
            },
            pointStart: 1
        }
    },
      series: [{
          name: 'Total earnings',
          color: '#79dcb4',
          data: history_contrib
      }]
  });
}

Live pages

Continuous time

  • Live pages allow to send data in continuous time
    • This module is needed for markets or live communication
  • Javascript is needed to take care of communication between server and clients
    • In the JavaScript code of the template insert function liveSend() to send data to the server.
  • In models.py in the class Player define a method to receive the message
class Player(BasePlayer):

    def live_message(self, data):
        print('received a message from', self.id_in_group, ':', data)

  • The name of the method should start with live_

  • In you Page set live_method to route messages to that method

- class MyPage(Page):
    live_method = 'live_message'

Example: submit a random number in real time

  • All players are asked to submit a random number that appears on their screen every 3 seconds
    • In real-time numbers are updated in a table

Template: HTML Code

  • In you HTML

    • A series of buttons to collect the value
<input class="mybutton" type="button" id="input_1" name="input" value="1">
<input class="mybutton" type="button" id="input_2" name="input" value="2">
<input class="mybutton" type="button" id="input_3" name="input" value="3">
<input class="mybutton" type="button" id="input_4" name="input" value="4">
<input class="mybutton" type="button" id="input_5" name="input" value="5">
<input class="mybutton" type="button" id="input_6" name="input" value="6">
  • A table with id history to show historical values
<table id="history" class="table">
    <tr>
        <th>Player</th>
        <th>Number</th>
    </tr>
</table>

Template: Javascript Code


{% block scripts %}

<script>

//send values
 $('.mybutton').click(function(){
     liveSend($('#' + this.id).val());
 });
 
// to "store" data in a table
    let history = document.getElementById('history');

    function liveRecv(data) {
        history.innerHTML += '<tr><td>' + data.id_in_group + '</td><td>' + data.disp_value + '</td></tr>';
    }
</script>

{% endblock %}
  • liveSend to send data to the server
    • Collect the value by id
  • let history = document.getElementById('history');
    • Returns the element that has the ID attribute
      • Collect data in the dynamic table with id=history
  • liveRecv
    • Called each time a message is received from the server
      • Writes a new line in table history
        • Values are obtained from the method defined in models.py

models.py and pages.py

class Player(BasePlayer):
    def live_broadcast(self, value):
        group = self.group
        my_id = self.id_in_group
        response = dict(id_in_group=my_id, disp_value=value)
        return {0: response}
  • A method to receive the message from the server
    • Values are stored in a dictionary
      • Values are passed to function liveRecv()
  • In pages.py insert the live method
live_method = 'live_broadcast'
